(1152, 'VIASPACE CEO to Present at International Fuel Cell Workshop', '', '<h5 align="center">VIASPACE CEO PRESENTATION AT INTERNATIONAL <br />FUEL CELL WORKSHOP</h5><p>PASADENA, Calif., October 10, 2007 - VIASPACE Inc. (OTC Bulletin Board: VSPC - News) CEO Dr. Carl Kukkonen gave an invited presentation at the New Energy Solutions International Workshop in Tours, France on October 9, 2007.&nbsp; The workshop focused on fuel cells and new energy sources in the micro watt to kilowatt range. Dr. Kukkonen&#39;s presentation was entitled &quot;Fuel Cells and Fuel Cartridge Infrastructure for Micro Fuel Cell Powered Portable Electronics.&quot; </p><p>The workshop addressed new fuel cell and battery power sources for portable electronics with increased performance and reduced environmental impact such as greenhouse gas emissions and use of heavy metals.</p><p>Dr. Kukkonen commented, &quot;There is a lot of new activity on fuel cells in Europe.&nbsp; This is driven by their desire to be as &quot;green&quot; as possible.&nbsp; Recently we have been working hard in Asia, but Europe also represents a significant international market.&quot;</p><p>VIASPACE subsidiary Direct Methanol Fuel Cell Corporation produces disposable methanol fuel cartridges that provide the liquid energy source for fuel cells that produce electricity for portable electronic devices such as notebook computers and mobile phones.&nbsp; These disposable cartridges represent a recurring revenue stream similar to printer cartridges or razor blades.&nbsp; The cartridges are made of recyclable materials, but international regulations state that they should not be refillable by the consumer for safety reasons.&nbsp; Several international companies such as Toshiba and Samsung have demonstrated notebook computers, cell phones and other devices powered by direct methanol fuel cells.&nbsp; A notebook computer running on methanol could have 10 hours of uninterrupted operation, and instantaneous recharging by simply replacing the empty cartridge with a new one.&nbsp; </p><p>About VIASPACE:&nbsp; Founded in 1998 to transform proven space and defense technologies from NASA and the Department of Defense into&nbsp; commercial&nbsp; hardware and software solutions that solve today&#39;s complex problems, VIASPACE benefits from important patent and software licenses from Caltech, which manages NASA&#39;s Jet Propulsion Laboratory.&nbsp; VIASPACE focuses on alternative energy and fuel cell infrastructure, and on hardware and software for security and defense.&nbsp; </p><p>For more information, please visit www.VIASPACE.com, or contact Investor Relations, Dr. Jan Vandersande, Director of Communications at 800-517-8050, or IR@VIASPACE.com.&nbsp; For past press releases, please visit: http://www.viaspace.com/press_release.php.</p><p><br />Investor Relations contact: <br />Dr. Jan Vandersande, Director of Communications <br />800-517-8050<br />IR@VIASPACE.com</p><p>Press contact: <br />Dr. Carl Kukkonen, CEO<br />626-768-3360 <br />-----------------------------<br /><em>This news release includes forward-looking statements.&nbsp; These forward-looking statements relate to future events or our future performance and involve known and unknown risks, uncertainties and other factors that may cause our actual results, levels of activity, performance or achievements to be materially different from any future results, levels of activity, performance or achievements expressed or implied by these forward-looking statements.&nbsp; Such factors include the risks outlined in our periodic filings with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, including our Annual Report on Form 10-KSB, as amended, for the fiscal year ended December 31, 2006, and our Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the period ended June 30, 2007, as well as general economic and business conditions, the ability to acquire and develop specific projects and technologies, the ability to fund operations, changes in consumer and business consumption habits, and other factors over which VIASPACE has little or no control.</em></p>', '2007-10-10 00:00:00', '', '', 1, 1, 1152, 1),
(1153, 'VIASPACE Subsidiary DMFCC Teams with ANTIG of Taiwan on Joint Development of Fuel Cell Products', '', '<h5 align="center">VIASPACE SUBSIDIARY DMFCC SIGNS TEAMING AGREEMENT WITH ANTIG OF TAIWAN FOR JOINT DEVELOPMENT OF FUEL CELL PRODUCTS </h5><p>PASADENA, CA -October 15, 2007-VIASPACE Inc. (OTCBB: VSPC) announced that Taiwanese Fuel Cell Developer ANTIG and VIASPACE subsidiary Direct Methanol Fuel Cell Corporation (DMFCC) have signed a teaming agreement to collaborate on the development of fuel cell systems that leverage ANTIG&#39;s innovative micro fuel cell stacks, along with Direct Methanol Fuel Cell Corporation&#39;s line of fuel cell cartridges and other products</p><p>Dr. Carl Kukkonen, CEO of both VIASPACE and DMFCC, stated &quot;Our teaming agreement with ANTIG is a key example of DMFCC&#39;s continued expansion of its global business strategy.&nbsp; We are partnering with top organizations that have a good reputation and the trust of customers in their own markets. We are honored to have a relationship with ANTIG, which is working with major commercial customers in Taiwan and elsewhere in Asia.&nbsp; We believe that this teaming agreement will benefit both organizations and will help fuel cells to reach the marketplace more quickly&quot;&nbsp; </p><p>ANTIG develops fuel cells and related products in collaboration with major electronics corporations in Taiwan and throughout Asia. DMFCC will partner with ANTIG on certain projects and will also extend IP protection to ANTIG and their customers for the extensive Caltech IP portfolio that DMFCC has licensed from Caltech and University of Southern California.</p><p>Brent McKendry, Antig CEO said that &quot;We are pleased to have this opportunity to work closer with DMFCC and believe it brings added value to all our partners who are currently building fuel cell systems.&quot; </p><p>VIASPACE is a growing company with proprietary technology, much of which was originally developed at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) and licensed from Caltech, which manages JPL for NASA. </p><p>VIASPACE has previously announced other strategic relationships in its VIASPACE Energy and VIASPACE Security business units..&nbsp; </p><p>About VIASPACE:&nbsp; Originally founded in 1998 with the objective of transforming proven space and defense technologies from NASA and the Department of Defense into hardware and software solutions that solve today&#39;s complex problems, VIASPACE benefits from important patent and software licenses from Caltech, which manages NASA&#39;s Jet Propulsion Laboratory.&nbsp; </p><p>For more information, please visit www.VIASPACE.com, or contact Investor Relations, Dr. Jan Vandersande, Director of Communications at 800-517-8050, or IR@VIASPACE.com.&nbsp; For past press releases, please visit: http://www.viaspace.com/press_release.php.</p><p>Press contact: Carl Kukkonen 626-768-3360 </p><p>About Antig: Antig is a leading developer of micro fuel cell stacks - the power generators inside a fuel cell system. Based out of Taipei, Taiwan, Antig currently has over 230 patents in the area of fuel cell stack and system design, and has been recognized worldwide for their innovative H2Chip<sup>TM</sup> technology.</p><p>Press Contact:<br />Linnet Tsai<br />+886 2 2656 2569 x 122<br />Email: linnet@antig.com<br />-----------------------------<br /><em>This news release includes forward-looking statements.&nbsp; These forward-looking statements relate to future events or our future performance and involve known and unknown risks, uncertainties and other factors that may cause our actual results, levels of activity, performance or achievements to be materially different from any future results, levels of activity, performance or achievements expressed or implied by these forward-looking statements.&nbsp; Such factors include the risks outlined in our periodic filings with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, including our Annual Report on Form 10-KSB, as amended, 