(74, 'Mechanical Design Engineer', '<p><strong>Summary:</strong> Mechanical design engineers spend the large portion of their time designing and engineering a variety of fuel cell devices and components. These are largely plastic parts made by injection molding or extrusion. The engineer will participate in design and integration phases and will interface with outsourced cartridge manufacturers and customers. Some travel to USA and within Asia will be required. </p><p><strong>Essential Duties and Responsibilities: </strong></p><ul><li>Oversight of Prototyping and fabrication skills; Demonstrated knowledge of DFMA principles.</li><li>Design, test, and implement manufacturing process tools, fixtures and equipment.</li><li>Design and test plastic parts</li><li>Analyze problems at suppliers and partner companies; recommend solutions; monitor and interface for resolution</li><li>Manage the overall technical development of the fuel cell products and coordinate efforts in the U.S. and other countries</li><li>FEA modeling and analysis.</li><li>Participate in program presentations and technical meetings.</li><li>Performs a variety of tasks. Some degree of creativity is expected</li></ul><p><strong>Supervisory Responsibilities:</strong> </p><ul><li>None Applicable</li></ul><p><strong>Qualifications:</strong> </p><ul><li>Bachelor&#39;s degree in Mechanical Engineering with 5 plus years of experience or equivalent combination of education and experience.</li><li>In-depth knowledge and application of engineering principles and concepts.</li><li>Working knowledge of Solidworks 2D and 3D (2006 preferable) and experience in detailing and GD&amp;T per ASME Y14.5M standards.</li><li>Prototyping and fabrication skills; Demonstrated knowledge of DFMA principles.</li><li>High level of initiative, with an ability to plan, manage tasks, conceptualize, implement, and validate solutions. </li><li>Demonstrated analytic and empirical problem solving skills.</li><li>Strong written and verbal English language communication skills.</li><li>Expertise in MS Office (Word, Excel, Power Point, Outlook).</li><li>Ability to communicate well at multiple management levels within a company</li><li>Program management experience</li><li>amiliarity with a product development cycle.</li><li>Demonstrated ability in designing plastic and metal parts.</li><li>Quality Assurance working experience.</li><li>Statistical analysis, reliability and six-sigma knowledge.</li><li>Participates in program presentations.</li><li>Can accomplish goals on projects following general guidance and supervision.</li><li>Prefer some prior experience on a technical team in research and/or product development </li></ul><p><strong>Work Environment:</strong> </p><ul><li>Work is performed predominantly in an office environment; occasional visits or activities in a manufacturing environment are required</li><li>Attendance at customers&#39; offices and job sites are required</li><li>Some overseas travel to customer facilities or manufacturing partners may be required</li></ul><p><strong>Physical Demands:</strong> </p><ul><li>Minor lifting up to 25 pounds may be required on occasion</li></ul>', 1, 74),
(75, 'Electronics Technician', '<p><strong>Summary: </strong>This individual will provide electronics assembly and troubleshooting skills, establish safety and assembly instructions, input to customer operations and maintenance manuals and provide general electronics lab support for new Viaspace products. This individual will order, track, store and inventory components, sub-systems and equipment associated with products. This individual will perform analysis and repair of equipment failures or maintenance issues and interface at times with Business Development in the establishment of customer service and support plans for new products. </p><p><strong>Supervisory relationship:</strong> This is an hourly wage, individual contributor position.</p><p><strong>Essential Duties and Responsibilities:</strong> </p><ul><li>Provide electronics technical skills in PCB (printed circuit board) and assembly testing and troubleshooting.</li><li>Design and build test setups.</li><li>Conduct electrical and electromechanical prototype assembly from schematics or from engineering drawings.</li><li>Test and troubleshoot software-driven electromechanical products in development format (alpha and beta versions) and in production format.</li><li>Provide feedback on assembled product prototypes to engineering and operations</li><li>Establish test procedures to certify products to applicable safety and regulatory requirements.</li><li>Conduct internal tests of new products as assigned.</li><li>Input to technical specification sheets, operating and user manuals</li><li>Support other new products or electronics equipment as they develop in fuel cells, cartridges and components as assigned.</li></ul><p><strong>Qualifications:</strong> </p><ul><li>A.S. degree or technical school minimum in electrical/electronics</li><li>Proven ability to use electronic test equipment such as oscilloscopes, digital multi-meters, DC power supplies.</li><li>Proven ability in the assembly of electrical/electronics equipment of various types and complexities</li><li>Advanced skill level in soldering (surface mount)</li><li>Proven ability to record data in an organized fashion and to follow/fill out a test plan with minimal oversight</li><li>Ability to handle multiple projects and tasks and to meet short deadlines</li><li>Current experience in technical development of new products and ramp up to manufacturing in high volumes</li><li>High level of initiative, with an ability to self plan and manage tasks</li><li>Demonstrated analytic and empirical problem solving skills.</li><li>Strong written and verbal English language communication skills.</li><li>Experience in MS Office (Word, Excel, Power Point, Outlook).Lab View experience a definite plus.</li><li>Ability to communicate well at multiple management levels within a company</li></ul><p><strong>Work Environment:</strong> </p><ul><li>Some minor amounts of travel within the U.S. and other countries may be required.</li><li>Work is performed predominantly in an office or lab environment; occasional visits or activities in a manufacturing environment may be required</li><li>Attendance at customers&#39; offices and job sites may be required</li></ul><p><strong>Physical Demands:</strong> </p><ul><li>Minor lifting up to 25 pounds may be required on occasion</li></ul>', 1, 75),
