(177, '', '<h4> </h4><p>The VIASENSOR HS-1000 Fuel Cell Humidity Sensor product has generated significant early interest in the marketplace and VIASPACE is expanding its customer base in the United States and Asia. The VIASENSOR is a proprietary, leading edge, laser-based test device that quickly and accurately determines the level of absolute humidity or water vapor flowing in a gas stream, which is vital to the proper function and efficiency of hydrogen fuel cells.</p><p>VIASPACE has received positive feedback from potential customers in several market sectors including major auto manufacturers, automotive test systems providers, fuel cell developers and suppliers to portable electronics OEMs.&nbsp;</p>', 1, 177),
(178, '', '&nbsp; <ul><li><span><span>o<span style="font: 7pt ''Times New Roman''"> </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Arial">Click on the left navigation item &quot;Page Manager&quot;<br /><br /></span></li><li><span><span>o<span style="font: 7pt ''Times New Roman''"> </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Arial">You will see all top level pages including: VIASPACE, VIASPACE Energy, VIASPACE Security, Ionfinity, Investor Relations, Articles and Other (Misc.)<br /><br /></span></li><li><span><span>o<span style="font: 7pt ''Times New Roman''"> </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Arial">For example, we will explain how to add a third level item under &quot;VIASAPCE &gt; About Us&quot;</span></li><li><span style="font-family: Arial"><span>1.<span style="font: 7pt ''Times New Roman''"> </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Arial">Click on the &quot;folder&quot; icon to the left of the VIASPACE listing</span></li><li><span style="font-family: Arial"><span>2.<span style="font: 7pt ''Times New Roman''"> </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Arial">Click on the &quot;folder&quot; icon to the left of the About Us listing</span></li><li><span style="font-family: Arial"><span>3.<span style="font: 7pt ''Times New Roman''"> </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Arial">Click on the &quot;ADD Page&quot; link in the upper right</span></li><li><span style="font-family: Arial"><span>4.<span style="font: 7pt ''Times New Roman''"> </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Arial">Click the radio button to select the &quot;1 COLUMN TXT ONLY&quot; template (this page will enable you to include additional templates in the future, if you choose to do so)</span></li><li><span style="font-family: Arial"><span>5.<span style="font: 7pt ''Times New Roman''"> </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Arial">Click &quot;Continue&quot;</span></li><li><span style="font-family: Arial"><span>6.<span style="font: 7pt ''Times New Roman''"> </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Arial">Type in a title</span></li><li><span style="font-family: Arial"><span>7.<span style="font: 7pt ''Times New Roman''"> </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Arial">Leave the URL blank if this is a brand new page you will be developing; if you would like to create link to an existing page on the site, or to an external site, copy and paste the entire URL in the URL field</span></li></ul>', 2, 60),
(179, '1. What is SHINE?', '<p>SHINE (Space Health INference Engine) is a software inference engine (expert system, ES) for the purpose of monitoring, analysis and diagnosis of real-time and non-real-time systems.&nbsp; It is a system developed at NASA to meet many of their demanding and rigorous AI goals for current and future needs.&nbsp; <br />It is a system that was designed to be efficient enough to operate in demanding real-time, and limited HW environments and to be utilized by non-ES applications written in conventional programming languages such as C, C++, and Java, etc.&nbsp; <br /><br />SHINE developed applications can run in a distributed computing environment, on remote computers, or on a computer that supports multiple programming languages and is ideal for real-time embedded applications, such as sensor fusion, security / surveillance, situational awareness, process control, or continuous monitoring of diagnostics, prognostics, or any application where intelligent systems needs to be hosted in small environments containing limited resources, such as embedded systems, smart sensors, specialized h/w devices, etc.</p>', 1, 179),
(180, '', '&nbsp; <li><strong><u>DSN Operations </u>: </strong>Created a Common Data Environment (CDE) project for diagnosing anomalies in the Deep Space Net (DSN). It operates in a real-time environment interfacing to an excess of 40 different legacy systems generating decisions and recommendations for control of the telecommunication systems.</li>', 1, 180),
(181, '2. What are the key features that differentiate SHINE from other previous or existing Expert Systems?', '<p>SHINE is the only available ES that is cross-compiler based.&nbsp; By this we mean a knowledge base is developed in a SHINE rule editor (VIASPACE Rule Editor, VUE), and then translated from its rule-based form (Syntax) to readable and optimized C/C++ source code output.&nbsp; <br /><br />The SHINE VUE development environment enables the developer to specify the program interfaces and system calls that the application will need, rather than telling the user what it wants.&nbsp; This is the critical difference that provides users complete flexibility in integrating the output of SHINE developed programs with any C/C++ or conventional language based application.<br /><br />SHINE is not a black box application where how it functions is a secret.&nbsp; SHINE takes a knowledge base rule representation as input, and compiles it in to a C/C++ source code function.&nbsp; This SHINE generated source code is under complete control of the user as to how it gets implemented or integrated into a final application.&nbsp;&nbsp; Nothing is hidden from the user.<br /><br />Because SHINE does not use the inference RETE Algorithm and uses a propriety Data Flow transformation, the performance of SHINE generated source code can always be determined in advanced.<br /><br />Because SHINE is a source-to-source compiler (SHINE rules: C/C++ Source code), a knowledge base can easily be verified for correctness, memory leaks, and performance using conventional C/C++ software development tools and methodologies.<br /><br />SHINE can deliver both soft and hard real-time performance so it can be used in critical applications such as automotive, man-rated, command and control, automation, Flight Software, etc.&nbsp; In addition SHINE generated source code can be complied by any standard RTOS compliers and the resulting executable run on any supported embedded hardware.<br /><br />Because of SHINE&#39;s determined and efficient memory allocation, lack of garbage collection, and lack of recursion present in complied SHINE source code, SHINE applications can be delivered and embedded in tiny processors, or constrained HW environments found in typical in automotive, avionics systems or process control applications among others.</p>', 1, 181),
(183, '', '', 0, 0),
(184, '3.  How does SHINE?s VUE knowledge representation or Rule syntax differ from traditional Expert Systems?', 'SHINE uses static fact instances that can have dynamic run-time values. As new facts are asserted or modified, they are monitored by the data flow program, causing the candidate rules to be executed.&nbsp; Any changes to the memory are directly mapped to the set of candidate rules.&nbsp; The antecedents of those rules are checked to determine if the consequences should be executed.', 1, 184),
(185, '4. Why has interfacing a traditional rule base or expert system (ES) been considered complex or difficult in C/C++?', '<p>In the past developing expert systems involved trying to integrate an existing expert system with C/C++ when the expert system was designed to function in strictly a stand-alone capacity.&nbsp; Traditionally, only the most elementary program interfaces (API) existed and they only allowed data to be sent to the system and the raw results captured and sent back to the calling C/C++ application.</p><p>Previous expert systems were designed to be totally self-contained and you were forced to implement your knowledge-based application as dictated by the designers of the system.&nbsp; Because SHINE translates a rule-based program in to a decision tree and generates user-readable source code, the user can always evaluate its final output.<br />Typically these ES used complex memory allocation strategies that were frequently incompatible with C++ application.&nbsp; SHINE uses conventional memory allocation strategies that are native to the C/C++ application and does not require any garbage collection.<br />Their performance was never known in advance because the performance of the inference algorithm was impossible to evaluate in advance.&nbsp; Because of this, ES are typically run on large computers requiring more than 100 MB of memory.</p>', 1, 185),
(186, '5. What are the key benefits of SHINE cross compiled source code?', '<p>SHINE does not use the RETE pattern matching algorithm typically used in traditional ES. Unlike conventional ES that translate the knowledge base to an internal form that is inefficiently interpreted by the rule-time system of the expert system, SHINE uses a proprietary Data Flow algorithm in which SHINE knowledge bases can be translated directly to C/C++ source code.<br />&nbsp; <br />Translated or cross complied SHINE programs contain no run-time support so they can execute directly by the target processor.</p><p>The proof in SHINE&#39;s performance is in the benchmarks that were performed that were designed to tests its raw performance.&nbsp; Running on a conventional laptop computer, it executed over 1.2 Billion rules per second.&nbsp; This is several orders of magnitude faster that it&#39;s best competition.</p>', 1, 186),
(187, '6. How do you ensure reliability and optimization of SHINE compiled source code?', '<p>SHINE does not provide the user with any advantage in producing bug-free code over that of any other expert system.&nbsp; The statement garbage in, garbage out also holds true for SHINE.</p><p>SHINE does however provide the advantage that because it is a source-to-source compiler; you have complete visibility into the code that it generates.&nbsp; This allows the software engineer to easily spot problems, whereas in a non-SHINE system you have no visibility into what is being generated.</p><p>Because SHINE is a source-to-source compiler, a knowledge base can easily be verified for correctness, memory leaks, and performance using conventional C++ tools.</p>', 1, 187),
(188, '7. What is the footprint of SHINE generated source code?', 'The size of a delivered SHINE complied source application is directly related to the complexity of the complied knowledge base (SHINE input Rules).&nbsp; For comparison, a typical knowledge base running in a non-SHINE expert system might need at least 50 MB or more of memory (the minimum footprint of the runtime ES executable itself, plus application logic).&nbsp;&nbsp; Whereas, SHINE requires only the memory that would be sufficient to represent the application logic itself.&nbsp; In this case, a conventional 50 MB expert system knowledge base would require less than 20 KB of physical memory.&nbsp; This is several orders of magnitude improvement in memory efficiency.', 1, 188),
(189, '8. How does SHINE allocate memory for different variables like static, dynamic and array?', 'SHINE does not use the RETE pattern matching algorithm, which requires dynamic memory allocation.&nbsp; SHINE uses a propriety Data Flow algorithm that computes in advance all the relevant paths through a knowledge base and compiles those paths directly into C code.&nbsp; The resulting program does not require any indexing of facts, which means no dynamic memory allocation needs to be performed.<br />All memory allocation for a SHINE program is done statically and is known in advance by the C/C++ compiler.', 1, 189),
(194, '', '<p>Direct Methanol Fuel Cell Corporation (DMFCC), a subsidiary in which VIASPACE holds a majority interest, is pursuing a significant market opportunity for disposable methanol fuel cartridges, valves and other components. These methanol fuel cartridges provide the energy source for tomorrow&#39;s fuel cell-powered portable electronic devices, such as laptop computers and cell phones. Fuel cells are expected to gain a substantial market share because they offer longer operating time as compared to current lithium ion batteries and may be instantaneously &quot;recharged&quot; by simply replacing the disposable fuel cartridge.</p><p>Methanol fuel cells are replacements for traditional batteries and are expected to gain a substantial market share because they offer longer operating time as compared to current lithium ion batteries and may be instantaneously recharged by simply replacing the disposable fuel cartridge. DMFC products are being developed for these applications by companies such as Samsung in Korea, and by Toshiba, NEC, Hitachi and Sanyo in Japan. Sales are expected to reach billions of dollars within a few years. With state of the art proprietary products, a global standard distribution network, and a comprehensive suite of fundamental fuel cell patents, DMFCC has a mechanism in place to advance this exciting new technology. </p>', 1, 194),
(195, '', '<strong>D</strong><strong>i</strong><strong>rect Methanol Fuel Cell Corporation</strong><strong> (DMFCC)</strong> is a provider of disposable fuel cartridges and intellectual property protection for manufacturers of direct methanol and other liquid hydrocarbon fuel cells. Methanol fuel cells are replacements for traditional batteries and are expected to gain a substantial market share because they offer longer operating time as compared to current lithium ion batteries and may be instantaneously recharged by simply replacing the disposable fuel cartridge. DMFC products are being developed for these applications by companies such as Samsung in Korea, and by Toshiba, NEC, Hitachi and Sanyo in Japan. Sales are expected to reach billions of dollars within a few years. With state of the art proprietary products, a global standard distribution network, and a comprehensive suite of fundamental fuel cell patents, DMFCC has a mechanism in place to advance this exciting new technology. <p>The direct methanol fuel cell was invented and developed at the Caltech/NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory and the University of Southern California (USC) and is protected by more than 59 issued and 59 pending patents worldwide.  DMFCC has license rights to the Caltech intellectual property portfolio for direct liquid hydrocarbon fuel cells (including direct methanol fuel cells, DMFC), electrode construction, membrane electrode assemblies (MEAs), fuel cell systems, methanol sensor and filter, electrolysis of methanol to form hydrogen, and methanol fuel cartridges.  Caltech and USC are founding shareholders in DMFCC.  VIASPACE Inc. and Itochu Corporation are also DMFCC&#39;s current investors.</p><p>DMFCC will work cooperatively with all fuel cell and electronics manufacturers worldwide to provide them the patent protection they need to bring their fuel cell products to market within a cost effective business model.  DMFCC and its partners will also work with fuel cell manufacturers and OEMs to develop custom cartridges for their applications, ensure that these cartridges meet exacting technical, safety, and child resistance standards, and are available to consumers at an attractive price.  DMFCC can also provide global cartridge distribution.</p>', 1, 195),
(196, 'DMFCC is the Intellectual Property Leader', '<p>The direct methanol fuel cell was invented and developed at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory and the University of Southern California (USC) and is protected by 59 issued and over 59 pending patents worldwide. DMFCC has license rights to this Caltech patent portfolio. DMFCC understands that it takes both great ideas and great people with the skill and know-how to turn ideas into marketable products that meet a growing demand. DMFCC wants to assist the fuel cell industry succeed. We believe that our seasoned team combined with our intellectual property portfolio will help fuel cell manufacturers and OEMs to bring their products to market by partnering with them to the missing pieces in their go-to-market strategies. DMFCC plans to work cooperatively with all fuel cell and electronics manufacturers in Japan, Korea, the United States and elsewhere to provide them the patent protection they need. DMFCC and its cartridge manufacturing and distribution partners plan to provide the industry with qualified sources of methanol fuel cartridges and develop the fuel cartridge infrastructure for manufacture and distribution. DMFCC also plans to work with customers and partners to develop direct methanol fuel cells for custom applications and crucial components for the fuel cell industry.</p>', 1, 196),
(197, 'Recurring Revenue Business Model', '<p>Direct Methanol Fuel Cells (DMFCs) are being developed for these applications by many, well-known international consumer electronic companies. Because the methanol cartridges are disposable, the cartridge business has the opportunity for recurring revenue. This consumer business will be similar to that of disposable batteries (e.g. AA), cigarette lighters or ink cartridges for printers with wide distribution and high volume sales. Low cost fuel cartridges are analogous to disposable alkaline batteries, but a cartridge containing 50ml of methanol could power a laptop for five or more hours compared to 10 minutes if an alkaline battery were to be used. When a laptop is plugged into the wall electrical outlet, no methanol would be consumed. A smaller cartridge can power a cell phone for up to 3 weeks.</p><p>Direct Methanol Fuel Cell Corporation has designed and developed plastic-based methanol fuel cartridge ranging from 6ml to 100ml. These include cartridges designed to be inserted into a laptop computer or similar portable electronic device. Other designs in development are for applications such as cell phones and PDAs.</p>', 1, 197),
(198, 'Standards in Support of Market Development', '<p>Safety codes and transportation regulations are being developed to ensure that this technology is safe for consumer use. Since 2002, DMFCC has been working with the fuel cell industry, Underwriters Laboratories (UL), CSA International and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), to develop international standards for the safety, performance, and interchangeability of methanol fuel cells and fuel cartridges. DMFCC fuel cartridges are designed to meet the highest standards and to comply with international safety and child safety regulations.</p>', 1, 198);
INSERT INTO `vspc_text` (`vspc_text_id`, `vspc_text_header`, `vspc_text_text`, `vspc_language_id`, `vspc_translate_id`) VALUES
(199, 'What is a DMFC?', 'Direct Methanol Fuel Cells (DMFCs) are alternative energy devices which can be used to power a wide range of portable and mobile electronics. DMFCs were invented at the Caltech/NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory with the University of Southern California (USC). <p>DMFCs are electrochemical devices that convert high energy density fuel (liquid methanol) directly to electricity. They operate silently, at relatively low temperatures and offer much longer operating time than today&#39;s batteries. Unlike a battery, DMFCs do not need to be recharged. They can provide electricity continuously to the consumer electronic devices as long as oxygen and fuel are supplied to the fuel cell. To achieve this, DMFCs can be &quot;hot-swapped&quot; and instantly recharged with replacement methanol cartridges (akin to batteries). Furthermore, this eliminates the need for consumers to carry electrical cords or adapters.</p><p>Methanol or methanol/water solution is the industry&#39;s choice of fuel. Because it is a liquid, it is easy to store and transport. Methanol is inexpensive and readily available. It also has very high energy density, which means longer operating time.</p>', 1, 199),
(200, 'How does a DMFC Work?', '<p>The heart of a fuel cell consists of catalysts for the electrochemical reaction and a special piece of plastic that can conduct protons. The technical term for this special plastic is polymer electrolyte membrane (PEM) and the most common PEM used in DMFCs today is Nafion<sup>TM</sup>, produced by Dupont. The most common catalysts used are PtRu alloy for the anode and Pt for the cathode.</p><p>In the fuel cell, the fuel is not burned, but rather is converted into electricity through an electrochemical process that splits methanol into protons, electrons, and carbon dioxide at the anode and then combines these protons and electrons with oxygen at the cathode to produce water. It is a very simple concept.</p>', 1, 200),
(201, '9. Why NASA trusts SHINE and has been using SHINE since last 10 years?', 'SHINE has been successfully applied to over a dozen applications both throughout NASA and within the commercial sector including flight hardware.&nbsp; It has significantly impacted operations cost, reliability and safety in eight NASA deep space missions that include Voyager, Galileo, Magellan and EUVE.&nbsp; In addition, it has been applied to medical applications for Welsh-Allyan and Johnson &amp; Johnson, Vialogy, and VIASPACE.', 1, 201),
(202, '10. What is Garbage collection and why should developers care about minimizing garbage collection?', 'Garbage collection (also known as GC) is a form of automatic memory management.&nbsp; The garbage collector or collector attempts to reclaim garbage, or memory used by objects that will never again be accessed or mutated by the application.&nbsp; John McCarthy, invented garbage collection around 1959, to solve the problems of manual memory management in his Lisp programming language.<br />Garbage collection is often portrayed as the opposite of manual memory management, which requires the programmer to specify which objects to deallocate and return to the memory system.&nbsp; However, many systems use a combination of the two approaches, and there are other techniques being studied (such as region inference) to solve the same fundamental problem.<br />&nbsp;<br />Garbage collection is a convenience provided to the programmer that sacrifices efficiency for simplicity in code development.<br />Implementing a program in a language that uses garbage collection presents several fundamental application limitations, such as:&nbsp; (1) Constraints running on small embedded processors because of memory and performance issues, (2) Non-guaranteed response times, as such applications cannot provide real-time performance because their behavior is never known in advance, (3) Typically cannot be delivered as a &quot;Mission Critical&quot;, &quot;Flight Code&quot; or man-rated application because the performance or system resources cannot be guaranteed in advance.<br />Popular languages that use garbage collection are JAVA and Microsoft&#39;s C#.', 1, 202),
(203, '11. How do you debug SHINE source code and what is the relation of SHINE cross-compiled code versus original knowledge/rules?', '<p>SHINE uses a proprietary Data Flow algorithm that translates or cross compiles knowledge bases directly to C code.&nbsp; Conventional ES systems translate the knowledge base to an internal form that is inefficiently interpreted by the run-time system of the expert system.</p><p>The advantage of a source-to-source compiler is that you have complete visibility into the code that it generates.&nbsp; This allows the software engineer to easily spot problems, whereas in a non-SHINE system you have no visibility into what is being generated<br />Because SHINE is a source-to-source compiler, a knowledge base can easily be verified for correctness, memory leaks, and performance using conventional C++ tools.&nbsp; A SHINE knowledge base can optionally specify a program interface (API) that it uses to automatically interface to the user&#39;s existing applications.&nbsp; No other expert system provides this capability nor can its internal representation for the knowledge base be interrogated by conventional software tools.</p>', 1, 203),
(204, '12. How is SHINE generated source code optimized during Code cross-compile phase?', 'SHINE introduces a novel paradigm for knowledge visualization and ultra-fast inference that goes well beyond traditional forward and backward chaining methodology. A sophisticated mathematical transformation based on graph-theoretic Data Flow analysis is introduced, that reduces the complexity of conflict-resolution during the match cycle from O(n2) to O(n) for many kinds of inference operations.<br />This transformation executes compiled SHINE knowledge bases at an excess of 16,000,000 rules per second on flight hardware and over 520,000,000 rules per second on a standard 2.2 GHz laptop system.&nbsp; This is several of orders of magnitude faster other commercial systems and delivers applications to resource-restricted platforms and embedded hardware.', 1, 204),
(205, '13. Is there any recommended C/C++ compiler?', 'SHINE was designed to work with ALL existing C/C++ compilers without any changes to the SHINE.  Including traditional Microsoft, Linux, and RTOS development tools.<br />SHINE works with both industry standard and internal propriety compilers so the SHINE tool itself never needs to be modified or extended to support new compilers.', 1, 205),
(206, '14. How can one measure the advantage of SHINE developed/compiled code versus traditional ?software developed? code?', 'Stereotypically, high-level languages make complex programming simpler, while low-level languages tend to produce more efficient code.<br />The term &quot;high-level language&quot; does not imply that the language is always superior to low-level programming languages - in fact, in terms of depth of knowledge of how computers operate the inverse may be true.&nbsp; Rather, &quot;high-level language&quot; refers to the higher level of abstraction from machine language.&nbsp; Rather than dealing with registers, memory addresses and call stacks, high-level languages deal with variables, arrays and complex arithmetic or Boolean expressions.&nbsp; In addition, they have no opcodes that can directly compile the language into machine code, unlike low-level languages like Assembly language.&nbsp; Other features such as string handling routines, object-oriented language features and file input/output may also be present.<br />In a high-level language, complex elements can be broken up into simpler, though still fairly complex, elements for which the language provides abstractions, keeping programmers from having to &quot;reinvent the wheel.&quot;&nbsp; For this reason, code that needs to run particularly quickly and efficiently may be written in a lower-level language, even if a higher-level language would make the coding easier.<br />However, with the growing complexity of modern microprocessor architectures, well-designed compilers for high-level languages can frequently produce more efficient code than most low-level programmers can do by hand.', 1, 206),
(207, '15. What is the RETE Algorithm [Wikipedia]', '<p>The RETE algorithm is an efficient pattern matching algorithm for implementing rule-based (&quot;expert&quot;) systems:</p><ul><li>The RETE algorithm was designed by Dr. Charles L. Forgy of Carnegie Mellon University in 1979</li><li>RETE has become the basis for many popular expert systems, including JRules, OPS5, CLIPS, JESS, Drools, and LISA</li></ul><p>The RETE algorithm provides the basis for a more efficient implementation of an expert system</p><p>A RETE-based expert system builds a network of nodes, where each node (except the root) corresponds to a pattern occurring in the left-hand-side of a rule.</p><ul><li>The path from the root node to a leaf node defines a complete rule left-hand-side.</li><li>Each node has a memory of facts which satisfy that pattern</li><li>As new facts are asserted or modified, they propagate along the network, causing nodes to be annotated when that fact matches that pattern.<br />When a fact or combination of facts causes all of the patterns for a given rule to be satisfied, a leaf node is reached and the corresponding rule is triggered<br />The RETE algorithm is designed to sacrifice memory for increased speed</li><li>In most cases, the speed increase over na&iuml;ve implementations is several orders of magnitude</li><li>In very large expert systems, however, the original RETE algorithm tends to run into memory consumption problems</li><li>The RETE algorithm requires interpretation of the network for each change to the memory and requires a large run-time footprint <br />VIASPACE Security</li></ul>', 1, 207),
(208, 'Disposable Cartridge Design & Safety Certification', 'Direct Methanol Fuel Cell Corporation&#39;s expertise lies in fuel cell cartridge design and safety certification. Since 2002, DMFCC has been working with the fuel cell industry, Underwriters Laboratories (UL), CSA International and the International Electrotechnical &nbsp;Commission (IEC) to develop international standards for the safety and performance of fuel cells and disposable fuel cartridges. DMFCC cartridges are designed to the highest standards, and to comply with the challenging international safety and child-resistance requirements.', 1, 208),
(209, 'Custom Designs for Your Application', 'Recognizing that each application may require a cartridge with a different size, shape, or feature, DMFCC will work in partnership with customers to rapidly develop and patent custom disposable cartridges for their specific applications.', 1, 209),
(210, 'Cartridge Manufacturing', 'DMFCC has cartridge manufacturing partners that have been certified to meet the international cartridge safety standards. DMFCC can also provide safety certification and manufacturing of cartridges designed by customers. If a customer has a preferred cartridge manufacturer, DMFCC will work with that manufacturer.', 1, 210),
(211, 'Global Distribution', 'DMFCC&#39;s cartridge distribution partners are developing a worldwide fuel cartridge infrastructure to support global sales of customers&#39; portable electronic devices. Please contact the company for further information.', 1, 211),
(212, '59 Issued & 59 Pending Patents Worldwide', 'The direct liquid hydrocarbon fuel cell was invented and developed by the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL), which is operated by Caltech, and the University of Southern California (USC). Hydrocarbon fuels include methanol, ethanol, formic acid, formaldehyde, dimethoxymethane and others.  Methanol is the most common fuel.  Caltech has 59 issued and 59 pending patents worldwide on the direct liquid hydrocarbon fuel cell technology.  Direct Methanol Fuel Cell Corporation (DMFCC) has license rights to all of these patents.  Caltech and USC are shareholders in DMFCC.', 1, 212),
(213, 'Extensive Patent Coverage', 'The Caltech patent portfolio includes the fundamental idea of a direct hydrocarbon fuel cell that uses a polymer electrolyte membrane (PEM), construction of the catalysts, anodes, cathodes, and membrane electrode assemblies (MEAs), as well as alternative membranes.&nbsp; Other patents include water recovery, methanol sensors and filters, monopolar geometry, and electrolysis of methanol to produce hydrogen.&nbsp; Contact the company for a copy of issued patents.&nbsp;', 1, 213),
(214, 'Partnering to Advance Fuel Cell Adoption', 'DMFCC will work cooperatively with fuel cell manufacturers and OEMs to provide them with the patent protection they need, using DMFCC&#39;s &quot;have made&quot;,&nbsp; &quot;import&quot;, and licensing rights.&nbsp; Instead of a license fee, DMFCC prefers to work with an OEM on a cartridge supply arrangement which would allow DMFCC to provide innovative and safe fuel cartridges specific to each fuel cell-powered device manufactured by the OEM.&nbsp; DMFCC and its partners will manufacture cartridges to an OEM&#39;s specifications, certify that the cartridges meet international safety standards, and distribute them on a global basis.&nbsp; If an OEM also desires to perform any of these functions, DMFCC is willing to work in partnership with the OEM.&nbsp; Using the cartridge approach, rather than requiring an upfront fee, DMFCC will share the market risk with the OEM and also will provide a valuable service by supplying cartridges to the marketplace.', 1, 214),
(215, 'DMFCC is partnered with two premier Korean firms to design and manufacture fuel cartridges to OEM specifications while meeting the highest degree of technical and international safety standards. ', '', 1, 215),
(216, '', '<p>SMC Co., Ltd., located at 398-1 Gochun-Dong, Euiwang-City, Kyonggi-Do, Republic of Korea , supplies lithium ion battery packs to OEMs of laptop computers, cell phones, PDAs, portable DVD players and other consumer electronics. SMC also produces Organic Light Emitting Diodes (OLED). SMC has manufacturing facilities in Korea and China. For more information please visit the web site at <a href="http://www.smcg.co.kr/" target="http://www.smcg.co.kr">http://www.smcg.co.kr/</a></p>', 1, 216),
(217, '', '<p>Elentec Co., Ltd. is a diversified company with electronic and portable power products.&nbsp; It produces lithium ion battery packs to power cell phones, PDAs, camcorders and laptop computers.&nbsp; Elentec is experienced in producing injection molded plastic parts, similar to fuel cartridges, and has 21 injection molding machines in its Suwon factory.&nbsp; Elentec is a leading Korean supplier of lithium ion battery packs for portable electronic devices to OEMs worldwide. For more information please visit the web site at <a href="http://www.elentec.co.kr/">http://www.elentec.co.kr/</a></p>', 1, 217),
(218, '', '<p>Sato Corporation of Tsu-city in Mie Prefecture, Japan was founded in 1954. The company&#39;s main business is manufacturing toner cartridges for laser printers. The company&#39;s key technologies are plastic injection molding and ultrasonic welding. Seed Corporation has 125 injection molding machines and 60 ultrasonic welders, and is on track to manufacture 200 million printer and toner cartridges in 2006 tier one equipment manufacturers.</p>', 1, 218),
(219, '', '<p>Hyun Won is a diversified technology company with offices in Korea, Canada, and the US. Hyun Won was founded in 1996, and is listed on the Korean stock exchange (KSDAQ). For more information please visit the web site at <a href="http://www.mobiblu.com/">http://www.mobiblu.com/</a></p>', 1, 219),
(220, '', '<p>Nypro, Inc, headquartered in Clinton Massachesetts, is the leading global, custom plastic manufacturer. Sales for the most recent fiscal year (end 6/30/2006) exceeded one billion dollars. Nypro is one of the largest U.S. employee-owned companies. For more information please visit the web site at <a href="http://www.nypro.com/">http://www.nypro.com/</a></p>', 1, 220),
(221, '', '<li><strong><u>Lockheed Joint Strike Fighter (JSF)</u>: </strong>Proprietary efforts using BEAM and SHINE for fault diagnosis.</li>', 1, 221),
(222, '', '<li><strong><u>Anomaly detection on F-18</u>: </strong>SHINE was delivered as part of BEAM anomaly detection system and ran on flight hardware. It performed real-time mode identification on two F-18 aircraft engines and was<span>&nbsp; </span>tested in F-18 hardware-in-loop (Iron Bird) simulator and actual flight tests. It executed on a ruggedized PC/104 computing hardware with streaming 1553 sensor data. It was proven on two static engine tests and six flights.</li>', 1, 222),
(223, '', '<li><strong><u><span>ETDP-On Board (AMES)</span></u></strong><span>: </span><span>Monitoring of flight system hardware and software with recovery.</span></li>', 1, 223),
(224, '', '<li><strong><u><span>SOMO (JSC CEV)</span></u></strong><strong><span>:</span></strong><span> </span><span>Tech transfer and experiment on robotics for crewed spaceflight.</span></li>', 1, 224),
(225, '', '<li><strong><u><span>Ares I FDDR (MSFC)</span></u></strong><strong><span>:</span></strong><span> </span><span>Conduct test and evaluation experiments to support fault monitoring and abort system design.</span></li>', 1, 225),
(226, '', '<li><strong><u><span>NAVSEA IVHM program (Navy)</span></u></strong><strong><span>:</span></strong><span> </span><span>Capability to rapidly determine combat readiness in crisis situations and prognostics of network health coupled with remediation.</span></li>', 1, 226),
(227, '', '<li><strong><u>Spacecraft Health Automatic Reasoning Pilot (SHARP)</u>: </strong>Diagnosis of telecommunication anomalies during the Neptune Voyager (VGR) Encounter.<span>&nbsp; </span>Prevented the possible loss of the entire mission by detecting a failing transponder long before it was possible by a human just 12 hours prior to the encounter. Recognition and medal from laboratory director.</li>', 1, 227),
(228, '', '<li><strong><u>X-33 Avionics Flight Experiment (AFE)</u>: </strong>Has been flown in support of the X-33 as part of JPL&#39;s Avionics Flight Experiment (AFE) as a Vehicle Health Manager (VHM).</li>', 1, 228),
(229, '', '<li><strong><u>Extreme UltraViolet Explorer (EUVE) Mission</u>: </strong>Labor reduction system to go from 3 to 1 shift reductions through the use of artificial intelligence. Recognition from Dan Goldin as an excellent of using AI for improving mission safety while reducing operational costs.</li>', 1, 229),
(230, '', '<li><strong><u>Galileo (GLL)<span>&nbsp; </span>Mission</u>: </strong>Mission for diagnosing problems in the Power and Pyro Subsystem (PPS).</li>', 1, 230),
(231, '', '<li><strong><u>Magellan (MGN) Mission</u>: </strong>Diagnosis of telecommunication anomalies in the TELECOM subsystem.</li>', 1, 231),
